is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;5h 16m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-17-choosing-the-right-pattern-for-a-top-worn-with-a-corset/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-17-choosing-the-right-pattern-for-a-top-worn-with-a-corset/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2017-11-30T17:42:26+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2017-11-30T17:45:18+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2017"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 17. Choosing the Right Pattern for a Top Worn with a Corset."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 17. Choosing the Right Pattern for a Top Worn with a Corset."><meta itemprop="description" content="I would like to do a small test and ask you several questions to solidify your knowledge. I wonder what you will answer. Go ahead and test yourself"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding and Evening Dresses. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding and evening dresses. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 17. Choosing the Right Pattern for a Top Worn with a Corset.</h1><p><strong>I would like to do a small test and ask you several questions to solidify your knowledge. </strong>I wonder what you will answer. Go ahead and test yourself!</p><p><strong>A small note before we move to the questions: </strong>I put my mock-up corset on the dress-form wrong side out just to have some contrast between the corset and the top. Of course you should put it right side out in reality.</p><p><strong>Task One. </strong></p><p><strong>The neckline of your corset is rather low in the middle. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2017.files/image002.jpg" alt="" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p><p><strong>A well-matching top will have a rather high U- or V-shaped neckline. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2017.files/image004.jpg" alt="" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p><p><strong>Question: &nbsp;what pattern will you use for the top? </strong></p><p><strong>Right answer: </strong>you should take the pattern of a corset with shoulders and give the desired shape to the neckline.</p><p><strong>Task Two. </strong></p><p><strong>It is the same low-neck corset but your client wants to wear it with a low-neck top. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2017.files/image006.jpg" alt="" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p><p><strong>Question: what pattern will you choose? </strong>It does not matter whether the top will feature straps going over the corset or straps coming from under the corset.</p><p><strong>Right answer: </strong>you should use the pattern with integrated shoulder straps.</p><p><img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2017.files/image008.jpg" alt="" class="img-responsive center-block"></p><p><strong>You should use this pattern because you want to achieve a well-fitting neckline in the décolleté area. </strong></p><p><img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2017.files/image010.jpg" alt="" class="img-responsive center-block"></p><p><strong>Thus </strong>you will choose the same pattern with integrated shoulder straps regardless of whether you want to make a low-neck corset, a low-neck top for wearing over a corset, or shoulder straps for a corset.</p><p><strong>And you should always remember that the top and the corset must share a common line of coordinates. This is usually the bust line positioned at the same level on both garments. </strong>You should take measurements from the same bust point for the top as for the corset.</p><p><img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2017.files/image012.jpg" alt="" class="img-responsive center-block"></p><p><strong>All patterns from my courses are combinable,</strong> i.e. they always have common lines so you can put together parts of different patterns. All my patterns are unified to avoid problems if you use them for constructing a top or shoulder straps for a corset, for example. All you need to do is choose the right pattern for the garment you want to make.</p><p><strong>I have a rather challenging final task for you. </strong></p><p><strong>Suppose your corset has a straight (strapless) neckline and you want to make a matching top with a low neckline and shoulder straps.</strong> For example, your client wants a see-through top with sleeves and a neckline which will reveal the straight neckline of the corset in the middle. It is quite probable.</p><p><img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2017.files/image014.jpg" alt="" class="img-responsive center-block"></p><p><img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2017.files/image016.jpg" alt="" class="img-responsive center-block"></p><p><strong>Question: what pattern will you use for the top? </strong></p><p><strong>You will be wrong to think that the pattern with integrated straps should work. </strong></p><p><strong>Right answer: you need to use the pattern of a corset with shoulders. </strong></p><p><strong>There is a simple explanation. </strong></p><p><strong>The straight neckline provides for some looseness between the cups. </strong>This area will never cling to the bust very tightly even though you will put a vertical bone in the centre of the front to form a depression between the cups.</p><p><img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2017.files/image018.jpg" alt="" class="img-responsive center-block"></p><p><strong>A top sewn after the pattern with integrated shoulder straps </strong>will push into this area between the cups of the corset, which will result in small wrinkles and creases. It will look as though the garment were too small for the client.</p><p><img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2017.files/image020.jpg" alt="" class="img-responsive center-block"></p><p><strong>Do not forget that your main goal is to achieve a snug fit along the neckline edge of the corset and not between the cups! </strong></p><p>The area between the cups looks just like it is supposed to look on a strapless corset.</p><p><strong>So make sure to cut the top after the pattern of a corset with shoulders. </strong></p><p><strong>The key conclusions we can make from this test-tutorial: </strong></p><p><strong>You need to use the pattern of a corset with shoulders for strapless corsets, boat-neck corsets, and, most often, for tops. </strong></p><p><strong>And you usually need to use the pattern of a corset with integrated shoulder straps for V-neck corsets and low-neck tops. </strong></p><p><strong>By the way, </strong>if you want to imitate a see-through top put under a V-neck corset (which is in fact a halter strap insert), then it makes sense to use the pattern of a halter corset.</p><p><img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%2017.files/image022.jpg" alt="" class="img-responsive center-block"></p><p><strong>I urge you to carefully analyze every case if you don’t want to end up with an ill-fitting garment. </strong></p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p><p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20boat.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Boat-Neck Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20strapless.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Strapless Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20V%20neck.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> V-Neck Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/corset%20-%20neck%20strap.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Corset wi